# Compute votes share only for parties above a certain threshold 
def parties_votes_percents(df, thresh):
    par = df.sum().div(df.sum().sum()).sort_values(ascending=False)
    return par[par > thresh]

votes = parties_votes_percents(df_2021, 0.035)  # total votes for each party
names = votes.keys()

Background¶

United Torah Judaism (Hebrew: , Yahadut HaTora), often referred to by its electoral symbol Gimel (), is a religious conservative political alliance in Israel. The alliance, consisting of Agudat Yisrael and Degel HaTorah, was first formed in 1992, in order to maximize Ashkenazi Haredi representation in the Knesset. Despite the alliance splitting in 2004 over rabbinical differences, the parties reconciled in 2006, in order to prevent vote wasting. In April 2019, the party achieved its highest number of seats ever, receiving eight seats. Unlike similar religiously-oriented parties like Shas, The Jewish Home, Tkuma, and Noam, UTJ is non-Zionist. However, unlike some other Haredim, the party is notable for its usage of technology and electronic communication.

For a party no political change was made between the two elections.

The party remained as it is without unification or separation from other parties. She ran in both elections when she addressed the same electorate with a change of chairmen at her head.

A.¶

The elections to the 24th Knesset marked a deep line in the Israeli political system. For the first time ever, and unusually also in relation For other democracies in the world, four elections were held in Israel in a very short time. The reason for this abnormal phenomenon lies in the fact that That the previous three incomes have failed to form a government.

In this report,we will analyze the "Yahadut HaTora" Party in the 2020 and 2021 elections and present a statistical analysis of its results and comparisons between them.

To write the report, we used the following files:

  • Voting data by polling station, voting data by locality (over election dates) - We used columns attributions to the voting data (for each party, kosher, bzb, invalid, name of town)
  • Ranking of localities by socio-economic cluster - We used the ranking to characterize the voters. Ranking of localities by level of peripherality - as above.
  • Division of localities into districts - as above.

To prepare the data, we took the following steps:

  • Downloading outer envelopes - Apart from the first item of the percentage of votes for the Torah Judaism Party, we decided to download The outer envelopes from the whole data for a number of reasons: they contain a vote of different and diverse populations and on Yes It is not correct to draw on the basis of indicative statistics (such as specific characteristics). Also, their bzb is zero, so some of the surgeries will not be feasible, as in correcting the votes by weighting. They are not suspicious ballots because Which incorporates votes from the general population and not by location or city. In addition to these, the percentage of votes for the Judaism Party The Torah from "outer envelope" ballots is negligible in its effect as and therefore can be removed to prevent distortion The surgery.
  • We turned the index of the polling station data according to the locality symbol and the polling symbol to the numbering of the polling station.
  • Reverse the index of the locality data by locality name.
  • We have created dictionaries to translate the letters of the parties to their names for clear presentation.

To begin with,we are interested in examining what the election results would have been if all people that have a right to vote would have voted. We assume that in every settlement/city the distribution of votes among eligible voters the choice that they did not vote or that their votes were invalid is the same as the distribution of votes of the kosher votes in the same locality. Nevertheless, in each locality the distribution may be different.

In [ ]:
def party_bar_fix(df1, df2, thresh):
    width = 0.3  # set column width 
    votes = parties_votes_percents(df1, thresh)  # total votes for each party
    n = len(votes)  # number of parties
    names = votes.keys()

    fixed_votes = parties_votes_percents(df2, thresh)

    rev_names = [name[::-1] for name in list(names)]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()  # plt.subplots()

    all_bar = ax.bar(np.arange(n), list(votes), width, color='b',alpha=0.6)
    fix_bar = ax.bar(np.arange(n)+width, list(fixed_votes), width, color='r',alpha=0.6)

    ax.set_ylabel('Votes percent')
    ax.set_xlabel('Parties Names')
    ax.set_title('Votes percent per party 2021')
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(n))
    ax.set_xticklabels(rev_names,rotation=-90)
    ax.legend((all_bar[0], fix_bar[0]), ('Real election', 'After correcting'))
    plt.show()

    return fig, ax

def gimel_copmare(df1, df2, thresh):
  width = 0.2  # set column width 
  votes = parties_votes_percents(df1, thresh)  # total votes for each party
  gimel_real = votes[' ']
  n = 1  
  fixed_votes = parties_votes_percents(df2, thresh)
  gimel_fix = fixed_votes[' ']
  fig, ax = plt.subplots()  # plt.subplots()
  all_bar = ax.bar(np.arange(n), gimel_real, width, color='b',alpha=0.6)
  fix_bar = ax.bar(np.arange(n)+width*1.2, gimel_fix, width, color='r',alpha=0.6)
  ax.set_ylabel('Votes percent')
  plt.ylim(0,0.09)
  ax.set_title('Resoults for "Yahadut Hatora"')
  ax.set_xticks(np.arange(n))
  ax.legend((all_bar[0], fix_bar[0]), ('Real election', 'After correcting'))
  ax.text(-0.03,0.059,str(round(gimel_real*100,3))+"%",size=14)
  ax.text(0.2,0.055,str(round(gimel_fix*100,3))+"%",size=14)
  plt.tick_params(
    axis='x',      
    which='both',      
    bottom=False,      
    top=False,        
    labelbottom=False)  
  plt.show()

  return fig, ax

Socio-Economic Analysis

We will now examine the socio-economic cluster of the voters of the Torah Judaism Party.

There is a division of localities according to a socio-economic cluster, with each locality being ranked in a number between 1 and 10. The meaning of the ranking is that locality that received 1 is in the lowest socio-economic cluster while locality that received the rating 10 is in the highest socio-economic situation.

At this stage, we performed two analyzes - one examining the percentage of votes for the Torah Judaism Party in each cluster and the other one is examining the percentages of Torah Judaism's voting by clusters.

E. Presentation of the vote for the Yahadut Hatora Party in all ballots in the form of a presentation by PCA:¶

In this section we will represent at the level unfolded by the first two PCA components the 2021 election ballots for all parties.** **The size of the circles in the plot, we made according to the percentage of votes for the Yahadut Hatora Party in each ballot box - the larger the circle, the higher the percentage the vote is higher. We will provide that we have normalized the according to the performance of the PCA so that all the ballots in the table are summed to one, so that the analysis be more informative (for all three graphs).

Note from the graph that the size of the circles, which show the percentage of votes for the Yahadut Hatora Party, increased at the center of the PCA axis The first (between -0.2 and -0.6) and in the negative part of the second PCA axis (between -0.2 and -0.6).

The meaning of the axes:¶

PCA one - characterize this axis as a symbol of nationality: low values - Jewish nationality, high values of Arab nationality.

PCA two - Divides the Axis by Religious-Political Ideology: High Values - Ideology of the Left, Low Values - Ideology of the right.

diff = pd.DataFrame(merge_df.iloc[:,0] - merge_df.iloc[:,1]) 

data_pca_2020 = ballot_2021[ballot_2021.columns[7:]].join(diff, lsuffix=" 2020",rsuffix=" diff", how='inner')
data_pca_2020 = data_pca_2020.iloc[:,0:39]
data_pca_2020 = normalize(data_pca_2020.T, axis=0)
our_pca2 = PCA(n_components=2)
x_pca2 = our_pca2.fit_transform(data_pca_2020.T)  # creating the B base (in R^9)
relevant_components2 = [x_pca2[:,0],x_pca2[:,1]]

# divide to 2 graphs- positive and negative + reisze the difference by mult by 2000
positive_cpa1, positive_cpa2, negative_cpa1, negative_cpa2, diff_pos, diff_neg =[], [], [], [], [], []

for i in range(len(diff)):
  if diff.iloc[i,0]<0:
    negative_cpa1.append(relevant_components2[0][i])
    negative_cpa2.append(relevant_components2[1][i])
    diff_neg.append(abs(diff.iloc[i,0])*2000)
  elif diff.iloc[i,0]>0:
    positive_cpa1.append(relevant_components2[0][i])
    positive_cpa2.append(relevant_components2[1][i])
    diff_pos.append(diff.iloc[i,0]*2000)
  else: ### dont show pts with 0
    pass

#creating the plot:
figure(figsize=(10,7))
plt.title("color by sign. and resize by absolute value of differneces  \n 2021 and 2020 of party: " + " "[::-1], fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('PC 1', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('PC 2', fontsize=12)
plt.scatter(positive_cpa1, positive_cpa2, s= diff_pos, 
            edgecolors="darkseagreen",c="honeydew")
plt.scatter(negative_cpa1, negative_cpa2, s= diff_neg, 
            edgecolors="brown",c="indianred")
plt.legend(labels=["positive","negative"],title = "sing")
plt.show()

Let us note that most of the circles are the same size (except for a number of large circles in which there was a significant change between two systems These elections), and this means that there was no extreme shift in the turnout between the 2020 elections and the 2021 elections. It can also be seen that the pink circles are more significant than the blue circles, meaning there was a positive difference in percentage Voting between these two systems. Here the PCA is reversed from before.

In conclusion, we have seen that the majority of votes for Torah Judaism come from polling stations characterized by right-wing religious and political ideology and that According to the observed trend, there is no significant difference between the election campaigns from 2020, to 2021. As we have noted, this figure is consistent with the fact that we saw the differences in the turnout between the two election campaigns and found that indeed the change in the turnout between them was minimal.

def process_matrix(merged_ballots_for_f, with_no_votes = False):
  data_voters = merged_ballots_for_f[[" 2021", " 2021", " 2021", " 2020", " 2020", " 2020"]] # choosing the columns and their order
  Nab = merged_ballots_for_f[[" 2020"," 2020"," 2020"," 2020"," 2020", " 2020" ," 2020","" ,""]] # 2020
  Nbb = merged_ballots_for_f[[" 2021"," 2021"," 2021"," 2021"," 2021","", " 2021" ," 2021" ,"","","" ,"" ,""]] # 2021
  if(with_no_votes):
      result = pd.concat([Nab, data_voters[" 2020"] - data_voters[" 2020"] - data_voters[" 2020"]])
      a = pd.DataFrame(data_voters[" 2020"] - data_voters[" 2020"] - data_voters[" 2020"])
      Nab = Nab.join(a,rsuffix = " ", how="inner")
      Nab = Nab.rename(columns={0: ' '})

      b = pd.DataFrame(data_voters[" 2021"] - data_voters[" 2021"] - data_voters[" 2021"])
      Nbb = Nbb.join(b, rsuffix = " ",how="inner")
      Nbb = Nbb.rename(columns={0: ' '})
  return(Nab, Nbb)

def corr_heat_map(M, parties_2021, parties_2020):
    n_21 = len(parties_2021)
    n_20 = len(parties_2020)

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10,10))
    im = ax.imshow(M, cmap=plt.get_cmap())

    ax.set_title("M - vote transition matrix")
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(n_21))
    ax.set_yticks(np.arange(n_20))
    # And to label them with the relevant parties names
    ax.set_xticklabels([n[::-1] for n in parties_2021], rotation=-90)
    ax.set_yticklabels([n[::-1] for n in parties_2020])
    ax.set_xlabel("2021")
    ax.set_ylabel("2020")

    # Loop over data dimensions to create text annotations.
    for i in range(n_20):
        for j in range(n_21):
            text = ax.text(j, i, round(M[i, j], 3), ha="center", va="center", color="w")

    # Create colorbar
    cbar = ax.figure.colorbar(im, ax=ax, shrink=0.55)
    cbar.ax.set_ylabel('votes probability', rotation=-90, va="bottom")

    plt.show()

def bar_plots(parties_2020, parties_2021, tops, names, seif_b = False, Y_2021 = False):
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 5, figsize=(20,10))
  width = 0.3  # set column width 

  votes_2020 = parties_2020[names].loc[tops]  # total votes for each party
  if seif_b:
    wanted_cities = tops.get_level_values(2)
    votes_2021 = parties_2020.reset_index().set_index(' ').loc[wanted_cities[0]].groupby(' ').mean()[names] # normalize by number of ballots in city

    for city in wanted_cities[1:]:
      votes_2021 = votes_2021.append(parties_2020.reset_index().set_index(' ').loc[city].groupby(' ').mean()[names] ) # need to normalize

  else:
    votes_2021 = parties_2021[names].loc[tops]  # do not normalize 

  rev_names = [name[::-1] for name in list(names)]
  n = len(names) 

  for ballot in range(10):
    title_top = str(tops[ballot][0]) +" " + str(tops[ballot][1]) + " " +tops[ballot][2][::-1]
    bar_2020 = ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].bar(np.arange(n), list(votes_2020.iloc[ballot]), width, color='b')
    bar_2021 = ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].bar(np.arange(n)+width, list(votes_2021.iloc[ballot]), width, color='r')
    ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].set_title(title_top, fontsize=14)

    ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].set_xticks(np.arange(n))
    ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].set_xticklabels(rev_names, rotation=90)
    if seif_b:
      ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].legend((bar_2021[0], bar_2020[0]),(' ',' '))
    else:
      ax[ballot//5, ballot%5].legend((bar_2021[0], bar_2020[0]),('2021 ','2020 '))
  for ax in ax.flat:
    ax.set_ylabel('Votes percent')
    ax.set_xlabel('Parties Names')
    
  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.show()

bar_plots(parties_2021, parties_2021, top_10_2021.index, names, True, True)  # Show ballots found in (b)

We see that the 10 polling stations that we presented above the turnout in Torah Judaism is very high compared to the average vote in the city. Let us note, that in none of the polling stations did we find the opposite relationship - that the average vote in the city for Torah Judaism is higher than the vote in a particular polling station.

Although there is an unusual vote for the Torah Judaism Party in the above 10 polling stations, we believe that this does not indicate a suspicion of forgery at those polling stations. We know that ultra-Orthodox society is characterized by the fact that the ultra-Orthodox live in areas close to each other and often these are the neighborhoods where the vast majority of the residents are only ultra-Orthodox. Thus, the exceptional polling stations are probably polling stations located in distinctly ultra-Orthodox neighborhoods (and in cities where the ultra-Orthodox population is not necessarily exceptionally high) and therefore in these polling stations the vote for the Torah Judaism Party is significantly higher than the city average.

Another way for finding suspicious polls is to compare the results of the 2020 election to the 2021 results.

We will examine the polling stations for which the square distance in the percentage of votes for the Torah Judaism Party is the highest. Let us note that in this way the characteristic of the party's ultra-Orthodox supporters who tend to live in close proximity to each other will not be affected since we look at the same ballot box in different election campaigns.

There are sometimes suspicious polls, that are worth for examination: Since we have seen that there was a transition from the Yahudut HaTorah Party to the Ziunot HaDatit Party, it is possible that the ballots in Jerusalem, Beit Zvi, Kfar Chabad, Emanuel and Safed are less suspicious compared to the rest. It might have happened because ultra-Orthodox-nationalist who did not want to vote for the United Right Party in the 2020 elections (since it is a less religious party than the "Religious Zionism" party that separated from it) but following the split in the Right Party they decided to vote for Ziunot HaDatit.

At the other ballots, the ballot box caught our eye in Haifa, where there was a great transition between the Arab parties in the 2020 elections and the Yahudut HaTorah Party. In our opinion, this is the most suspicious polling station of all the polling stations that our survey raised, since these are parties that appeal too significantly different populations.

Final Conclusion:

We have conducted a statistical analysis of the Yahadut HaTora in the last election campaigns: between 2020 and 2021 years. In the analysis, we characterized the party's voters in the 2 election campaigns by division voters into socio-economic level, right or left beliefs also taking into account in which localities and polling stations the party was stronger and which was weaker and we had checked the suspicious polling stations as well.

Therefore, we need to draw few conclusions:

  • Actual Turnout for Yahadut HaTora: we recognized that the turnout of the Yahadut HaTora is higher than the national turnout and that this figure is in its favor. Non-voting of the potential voters of other parties strengthens the seats won by Torah Judaism. We recommend that the party act to preserve and further increase the percentage of votes cast by its potential voters while trying to preserve the relative indifference of the other voters.
  • Voting turnout: We have seen that the party voters mostly have a religious character, at a low socio-economic level, mainly from the cities of the center and in the Jerusalem and Judea and Samaria districts. Consequently, we recommend turning to the party's activities to improve social conditions due to the low socio-economic level of its voters and thus persuade more of them to vote for it, along with continued action at the religious level in central cities and communities in Jerusalem and Judea and Samaria to preserve its political power. Alongside this, due to its weak power as far as the districts including the Central District and the Northern District are concerned. We also recommend running massive campaigns In these districts to increase the percentage of votes in them to the party and thus increase its power.

  • Locality: We identified that the party is mainly strong in localities of a religious nature and very weak in localities with an Arab or secular population. Therefore, we recommend strengthening the party's activities for the residents of the religious communities along with increasing political activity in these areas to strengthen it in them.

  • Vote transitions and influence: We have identified that the voice transition from the party to or from other parties is relatively small and it manages to maintain its power. When there is a transition of votes, it is usually in religious right-wing parties such as Shas. However,it will be difficult for the party to garner votes from across the political map and strengthen its power. So it would be good for party to carry out campaigns mainly with the ultra-Orthodox religious public and in the religious localities and that it act with the religious right-wing parties in order to strengthen its power among the electorate and to prevent and even attract new votes.

  • We also saw that the inclusion of non-voters in the transition matrix does not improve the quality of the forecast for a "Yahadut HaTora" scholarship, since the party enjoys a particularly high percentage of votes, as presented in Section H.
